Although Ri has recycled North Korean complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” approach to denuclearization, in which North Korea would be rewarded as it took gradual steps, his statements appear to be significant in that they do not marginally reject previous denuclearization measures.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit held between a US president in office and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim pledged to work towards “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump offered security assurances to North Korea.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to soften tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘denuclearization first’ and increases the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive way, opposing even the ‘declaration of an end to war’,” Ri said.
