These cells, which can “see” a protein common to many cancers, are then injected back into the body.
An experimental vaccine is producing promising results in patients with a number of cancers.
A woman treated with the vaccine, which teaches the immune system to recognize harmful cells, saw her ovarian cancer disappear for more than 18 months.
The method involves extracting immune cells from a patient and altering them in the laboratory so that they can "see" a protein common to many cancers, called HER2. These cells are then re-injected into the body.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “Our results suggest we have a very promising vaccine.”
HER2 "controls the growth of various types of cancer", including those in the breast, ovary, lungs and also colorectal, Professor Berzofsky explained.
An approach similar to that involving removing immune cells from patients and “teaching” them to attack cancer cells has worked in the treatment of a type of leukemia.
