New German warship once again postponed
The latest German navy frigate should have entered service in 2014 to replace Cold War-era warships. However, it will be necessary to wait at least until next year, due to systems prone to breakdowns and an exponentially growing cost, according to local media.
The entry into service of the "Rheinland-Pfalz", the command ship of the newest frigates of the Baden-Württemberg class, has now been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit citing a military spokesman.
The vessel should have joined the navy in 2014, but the troubling post-delivery problems undermined the fate of the ambitious project.
The four ships of the Baden-Württemberg class commissioned by the navy in 2007 will be used to replace the aging Bremen-class frigates.
It is known that they will be equipped with a powerful cannon, as well as a series of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as some stealth technologies such as the reduction of radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Other important features include more extended periods between maintenance, which would allow sending the latest frigates on missions with a maximum duration of two years away from the ports of origin.
However, the ongoing delays have meant that with state-of-the-art warships, considered as a way for Germany to design power across borders, they will already be out of date when they enter service, Die Zeit reports.
The unfortunate F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German navy refused to put it into service, having returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyards in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to the shipyard after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but the German media cites a number of crucial "hardware and software flaws" that would render the warship useless if used in a combat mission.
The software shortcomings were particularly important, as the ships of the Baden-Württemberg class will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors, only half of the contingent needed in the oldest frigates of the Bremen class.
It is also known that the vessel is excessively heavy, which reduces its performance and limits the Navy’s ability to install additional functionality in the future.
The 7000-ton Rheinland-Pfalz is believed to have twice the weight of similar class ships used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to hardware failures, the cost of the entire project, including crew training, is also becoming a problem.
This is said to have reached an astonishing <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>3.1 billion, an increase from the <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion initially budgeted.
The problems that plague the most recent frigates have become particularly important in light of recent warnings that German naval power is weakening.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, leader of the German parliamentary defence committee, acknowledged that the navy is currently running out of ships capable of being used.
The politician said the problem grew exponentially over time, as older ships were put out of service without any vessels to replace them.
In the end, he regretted that none of the frigates of the Baden-Württemberg class had been able to join the navy.
National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
New research is being conducted on a property in the Scottish Highlands with the aim of revealing how bats use the landscape to search for food.
The results are expected to shed some light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help guide conservation activities in the future.
The study, conducted by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, will follow common and fruit bats, as well as long-eared browns and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations scattered throughout the property to follow bat activities throughout the season.
Mobile studies will also be carried out by NTS staff and by volunteers with portable detectors.
Expert analysis of all recordings will assess the frequency of bat calls and what each species is doing.
A map of the habitat will then be produced to create a detailed picture of their behaviors on a territorial scale.
Rob Dewar, NTS Nature Conservation Advisor, hopes the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of meadows, as well as the best way to effect forest maintenance for bats and associated species.
Flea populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined considerably over the past century.
These animals are threatened by the construction and development work that affects the dormitories and make the habitat scarce.
Wind turbines and lightning also pose a threat, along with fly killer papers and some chemical treatments of building materials, in addition to domestic cat attacks.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, given their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo locating technique to identify insects and obstacles in their flight trajectory.
The NTS, responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the region, takes bats very seriously.
The organization has ten trained specialists who regularly carry out studies, inspections of dormitories and sometimes rescues.
He also came to create the first reserve in Scotland dedicated exclusively to bats, on the Threave property in Dumfries and Galloway, which houses eight of the ten species of Scottish bats.
The property manager, David Thompson, says the same is the ideal territory for them.
“Here in Threave we have an excellent area for bats,” he said.
“We have the old buildings, a lot of old trees and all this good habitat.
However, there’s still a lot about bats we don’t know about, so the work we’ve done here and on the other properties will help us know more about what they need to flourish.”
He stressed the importance of checking for bats before carrying out maintenance on the properties, as the unintentional destruction of only one maternity dormitory can lead to the death of up to 400 females and young animals, which could eradicate the entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill them, harass them, disturb them or destroy their dormitories.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to participate to help.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of our species, we simply don’t know how their populations are getting revenge.”
