Jack Ross: "My last ambition is to guide Scotland"
Sunderland coach Jack Ross has said his "last ambition" is to become Scotland's national team.
The 42-year-old has been successful in the challenge of giving new life to the northeastern club, currently third in the Premier League, at three points of leadership.
He moved to the Stadium of Light this summer after guiding St. Mirren on his return to the Scottish First Division last season.
“I wanted to represent my country as a player.
But I only got a B internationalization," Ross told BBC Scotland's Sportssound.
“I grew up watching Scotland play in Hampden with my father and these are some of my best memories.
But this opportunity will only arise if you are successful in managing clubs.”
Ross's predecessors as Sunderland coach include Dick Advocaat, David Moyes, Sam Allardyce, Martin O'Neill, Roy Keane, Gus Poyet and Paulo Di Canio.
The former Alloa Athletic coach says he didn’t feel afraid to follow up on such well-established names at such a large club after rejecting invitations from Barnsley and Ipswich Town.
“For me, for now, success is all about ‘can I take the club back to the Premier League?’”
Considering the structure and facilities of the club, their place is undoubtedly in the Premier League," he said.
"It won't be easy to take the club back, but I will only consider that I was successful here when I achieved that goal."
Ross's coaching career is only three years old, after a period as Dumbarton's deputy coach and 15 months on the Hearts technical team.
He then helped Alloa recover from the descent to the third division and led St. Mirren from the threat of depromotion to the championship title the following season.
Ross says he feels more comfortable now than he ever felt during his playing career at Clyde, Hartlepool, Falkirk, St. Mirren and Hamilton Academic.
Taking care of the Alloa "was a real crossroads," he recalls.
“I’ve always seen myself more as a coach than a player.
It sounds weird because it went well, I earned my life as a player and I had some high moments in my career.
But playing can be very hard.
We face many challenges every week.
I still face them in terms of the stress and pressures of the position, but I feel very good as a coach.
I’ve always wanted to train and now that I do, I feel more comfortable than I’ve ever felt in my adult life.”
You can listen to the full interview on Sportssound, on Radio Scotland, on Sunday, September 30, between 12:00 and 13:00 BST
