Europe wins Ryder Cup in Paris
The European team beats the U.S. and wins the 2018 Ryder Cup with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 at Le Golf National on the outskirts of Paris, France.
The U.S. has now accumulated six consecutive defeats on European soil since the last time they won the Ryder Cup in Europe in 1993.
Europe is once again victorious after the team of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn hit the 14.5 points they needed to beat the United States.
U.S. star Phil Mickelson, who proved to have serious difficulties during nearly the entire tournament, threw the starting tee into the water in hole 16, par 3, giving victory to Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari shined in all of his rounds, becoming one of four players to score 5-0-0 since the current format of the tournament began in 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth lost 5&4 to the worst-ranked player in the European team, Thorbjorn Olesen of Denmark.
The world's top-ranked player, Dustin Johnson, lost 2 and 1 to England's Ian Poulter in what may have been his last participation in the Ryder Cup.
A veteran of eight Ryder Cups, Spanish Sergio Garcia has become the most award-winning European of all tournaments with 25.5 career points.
“It’s not my habit to cry, but today I couldn’t stop myself.
