Updated information on the Red Tide: Concentrations decrease in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to new information from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission, there has been a decrease in Red Tide concentrations in some areas of Tampa Bay.
The FWC reported that conditions of lesser proliferation of spots were identified in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a decrease in concentrations.
The Red Tide spot extends about 201 km along the coast, from Pinellas County to the north to Lee County to the south.
Spots may be found about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer areas than last week.
The Red Tide was also spotted in Pasco County.
Last week, there were recorded average concentrations near or off the coast of Pinella County, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, bottom to high concentrations in Manatee County, bottom to high concentrations near or off the coast of Sarasota County, bottom to high concentrations in Charlotte County, and high concentrations in Charlotte County.
There are still reports of respiratory irritation in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
In the past week, there have been no reports of respiratory irritation in the northwest Florida region.
